results.reasoning: Ultrasound demonstrates a thin, avascular central septum partially dividing the endometrial cavity with the gestational sac/foetus extending across both hemicavities and placental tissue implanted on/near the midline septum. These findings are characteristic of a septate uterus. Bicornuate or didelphys would show a prominent external fundal cleft and more muscularly separated horns; an arcuate uterus is only a shallow indentation and does not produce a persistent thin midline septum, and intrauterine synechiae are usually irregular adhesions. Hence the most likely diagnosis is gravid septate uterus with septal placental implantation (Option C).

Core biopsy shows dense stromal fibrosis with a nodular lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate, abundant CD138+ plasma cells with >50 IgG4+ plasma cells/HPF and polyclonal kappa/lambda expression. Eosinophils are present and no malignant epithelial cells were identified. These features are diagnostic of IgG4-related breast disease (IgG4-related sclerosing mastitis). Monoclonality would be expected for a lymphoproliferative disorder and malignant cells for invasive carcinoma or DCIS, while papillomatosis would show epithelial papillary proliferation, none of which are present here.

Clinical presentation of chronic flank discomfort, anaemia and leukocytosis with imaging demonstrating the CT 'bear-paw' sign, renal enlargement with parenchymal destruction, staghorn/nephrolithiasis, perirenal abscess and a nonfunctional kidney is classic for xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis (diffuse form). Ultrasound findings of multiple thick-walled collections and loss of corticomedullary differentiation support this. Definitive confirmation by nephrectomy histology showing lipid-laden (foamy) macrophages confirms XPN. Other options (pyonephrosis, TB, tumour, hydronephrosis) are less consistent with the combination of bear-paw appearance, staghorn calculus and characteristic histology.

Imaging showed a large hypoechoic, fibrotic-appearing lesion with indistinct margins and non-mass enhancement—features that can mimic carcinoma. Histology demonstrated dense lymphocytic infiltrate, collagenised stroma and thickened basement membrane with no malignant cells, which is diagnostic of sclerosing lymphocytic mastitis (lymphocytic mastopathy/diabetic mastopathy). The association with impaired glucose tolerance/diabetes and complete resolution with conservative management further supports this diagnosis. Therefore the correct answer is C.

Biopsy confirmed a WHO grade IV pineoblastoma (high Ki-67 >40%) in the pineal region, with hydrocephalus and CSF-positive malignant cells (Chang stage M3). Imaging and clinical course fit a high-grade pineal parenchymal tumour rather than germ cell tumour or other lesions. Management with craniospinal irradiation and boost is appropriate for pineoblastoma with CSF dissemination. Therefore the correct diagnosis is Pineoblastoma (Option E).

Postoperative CT-urography with delayed/excretory-phase imaging demonstrates opacification of a pelvic fluid collection directly from the distal right ureter, indicating contrast-containing urine extravasation. This appearance is diagnostic of an iatrogenic ureteral injury with resultant urinoma rather than abscess, seroma, ascites, or extraluminal enteric material. Clinical context (recent colectomy, prior surgery, worsening pain/fever) further supports this diagnosis.

Slow-growing well-defined mass in the carpal tunnel abutting the tendon sheath with low–intermediate T1 signal, predominantly low T2 signal (reflecting dense collagenous stroma) and inhomogeneous enhancement is characteristic of fibroma of the tendon sheath (tendon sheath fibroma). Imaging and clinical features (location, chronicity) differentiate it from ganglion (fluid signal), GCTTS (hemosiderin susceptibility), nodular fasciitis (rapid growth) and fibrous histiocytoma. Therefore the most likely diagnosis is A: Fibroma of the tendon sheath.

Clinical picture of febrile left‑quadrant pain with leukocytosis and imaging showing a well‑defined mesenteric cystic mass with fluid–fluid levels (water to fat attenuation) and chylous/fat content, multiloculated appearance, plus peripheral enhancement and adjacent fat stranding (consistent with superinfection) is classic for mesenteric lymphangioma complicated by inflammation. Other cyst types (enteric duplication, mesothelial or enteric cyst) typically contain serous fluid without fat attenuation, and no history of pancreatitis argues against a non‑pancreatic pseudocyst. Histopathology in the case confirmed lymphangioma with inflammatory changes.

Initial CT showed a saccular aneurysm from a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer in the mid descending aorta. Subsequent imaging demonstrated loss of the periaortic fat plane, periaortic gas/intramural air, hazy aortic wall, enlargement of the saccular aneurysm, and contrast extravasation into the gastric fundus. These CT findings—ectopic gas adjacent to the aorta, intramural air, loss of the fat plane, and direct contrast leakage into the gastrointestinal tract—are classic for an aortoenteric communication. Surgical exploration confirmed an aortoesophageal fistula. Therefore the most likely diagnosis is E. Aortoesophageal fistula.

Young patient with a unilateral solid ovarian mass with cystic areas and biochemical hyperandrogenism (elevated delta-4-androstenedione) strongly favors an androgen-secreting sex cord–stromal tumor. Imaging (well-defined solid mass with peripheral cyst) and the clinical context are typical for Sertoli–Leydig cell tumor (SLCT). Fibroma/thecoma would be T2-hypointense and not androgenic; granulosa cell tumors are estrogenic; sclerosing stromal tumor has a characteristic enhancement pattern. Therefore the most likely diagnosis is Sertoli–Leydig cell tumour (Option C).
